		<h1>Here's hoping<br/>for some good genre efforts</h1>

		<div class="col">
			<p>Hope springs occasional in the movie business. As that business scrambles to anticipate (digitally or otherwise) what we watch, the way we watch it and where, one season ends and another begins. The summer of the billion-dollar-grossing "Trans- formers 3" (subtitle: "Better Than 'Transformers 2' ") slides into au- tumn, and the autumn leaves of red and gold pile up the way autumn leaves do.</p>
			<p>Audiences have picked up on the nervousness of the industry and the derivative aura coming off so many multiplex titles this year. Even the enjoyable superhero films this sum- mer couldn't prevent a person from thinking: Enough. By the time "The Avengers" arrives next spring, it'll feel like a remake.</p>
			<p>Not long ago producer Jeffery Katzenberg had this to say to For- tune's Andy Serwer regarding 2011, which no one will remember as the year of the "Clash of the Titans" and "Conan the Barbarian" do-overs:</p>
			<p>"Let me have a show of hands of
