			<p class="no_indent">people that would say the last seven or eight months of movies is the worst lineup of movies you've experience in the last five years of your life. ... It's unbelievable how bad movies have been." We'll know soon if Katzenberg's latest, "Puss in Boots," a spinoff of the "Shrek" franchise, will improve that lineup.</p>
			<p>Like everyone in Hollywood, Katzenberg has a vested interest in trashing the competition but he's also very possibly right. When a picture such as "The Help" hangs in there and attracts audiences week after week, what can a studio executive in a position to get movies made, actually made, learn from its success? Not much beyond the old, elusive story, really. Heart. As the mogul says in "Barton Fink": "Thanks for your heart, Bart. We need more heart in motion pictures." That, plus a best-selling title, along with some truthful
